caption: Table 1: Input- and output-based evaluation results of the methods and their ensembles, over different feature types and models, averaged across model layers, along with their respective 95% confidence intervals. For SAE features we take the average over features from SAEs of all sizes. We denote MA for MaxAct, VP for VocabProj, TC for TokenChange, and EnsembleR and EnsembleC for the raw and concatenation based ensembles.
description: This table presents a comprehensive evaluation of different methods for generating feature descriptions in large language models (LLMs).  It compares three methods: MaxAct (input-centric), VocabProj, and TokenChange (both output-centric).  The evaluation is two-fold: input-based (how well the description captures the inputs that activate the feature) and output-based (how well the description captures the causal effect of feature activation on model outputs).  Results are shown for various feature types (neurons in MLP layers, features from Sparse Autoencoders (SAEs) across different LLM sizes and architectures.  Performance is reported as accuracy, averaged across model layers, with 95% confidence intervals provided.  The table also includes ensemble methods combining the three main techniques (Ensemble Raw and Ensemble Concat), showing the benefits of combining input and output centric approaches.

This allows for a nuanced understanding of how effectively each method captures different aspects of the feature's meaning.

description: This table presents the results of an experiment comparing four variations of the VocabProj method for generating feature descriptions. The variations differ in how tokens are selected for input into the method, using either the encoding or decoding matrix of a model's vocabulary, and whether the tokens are retrieved from the embeddings or unembeddings. The results show the confidence intervals of the mean input metric score (measuring how accurately the description captures what triggers the feature) for each variation across different models and feature types.

description: This table presents the results of an experiment comparing two variants of the VocabProj method for generating feature descriptions.  VocabProj projects a feature vector into the model's vocabulary space to identify relevant tokens. The two variants differ in whether they use the unembedding or embedding matrix for the projection. The table shows the mean input metric scores (with 95% confidence intervals) for each variant across different models and layers. The input metric measures how accurately the description captures the inputs that trigger the feature. This experiment helps determine which matrix (unembedding or embedding) yields more accurate feature descriptions based on input-centric evaluations.

The table allows for comparison of the different methods' performances, highlighting the benefits of incorporating output-centric information into feature descriptions.
